<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>November 2013</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from Arthritis Research UK (PHE 000</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">9</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Public Health England accountability hearing</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Arthritis Research UK welcomes the opportunity to provide a written submission to the House of Commons Health Select Committee for its accountability hearing with Public Health England.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> We would be pleased to expand on the points below, and provide further information to the Committee.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Arthritis Research UK is the UK’s fourth largest medical research charity. Our vision is ‘a future free from arthritis’. Our remit includes arthritis and musculoskeletal conditions, which are disorders of the joints, bones and muscles – including back pain – along with rarer systemic autoimmune diseases such as lupus.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Together, these conditions affect around ten million people across the UK and, at £5 billion, account for the fourth largest NHS programme budget spend in England.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Arthritis is the biggest cause of pain and disability in the UK, and each year around 20% of the general population consult a GP about a musculoskeletal problem such as arthritis.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> As a charity we fund research, provide information to patients and educational resources for healthcare professionals.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The importance of musculoskeletal health in public health</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Public Health England’s mission is to protect and improve the nation’s health and to address inequalities. Musculoskeletal conditions have a substantial impact on the health and wellbeing of the UK population. The World Health Organization describes such conditions as ‘leading causes of morbidity and disability, giving rise to enormous healthcare expenditures and loss of work’.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Analysis of the Global Burden of Disease 2010 identifies musculoskeletal cond</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">itions as the largest contributor to the burden of disability in the UK – in 2010, such conditions accounted for 30.5% of all Years Lived with Disability (YLDs). The prevalence of musculoskeletal conditions is also rising over time.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Musculoskeletal problems are a major contributing factor to frailty. Loss of independence can be due to severe joint and back pain; or increased risk of fragility fractures due to age-related weakening of bone (osteoporosis) combined with joint and muscle weakness leading to falls. In 2011-12, over 59,000 people in England had a hip fragility fracture.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Musculoskeletal conditions also account for a significant proportion of workplace absence: 7.5 million working days are lost each year due to musculoskeletal conditions, second only to stress, depression and anxiety.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Osteoarthritis is the most common type of arthritis: 7.3 million people have sought treatment for the condition in England. It affects one in three people over the age of 45, many of whom are in the working population.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In her 2011 Annual Report, the Chief Medical Officer (CMO) for England described osteoarthritis as ‘an unrecognised public health priority’.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Moreover, </span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">musculoskeletal health is a data poor area </span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">little information collected nationally about these conditions or the care the NHS provides for people living with them. There is a need for greater detail in data collection relating to the incidence, prevalence and geographical distribution of musculoskeletal conditions, as well as the impact they have on people living with them, and upon health and care service and wider society, including economic data. Indeed, the Chief Medical Officer recognised that ‘national data on the full extent and impact of some musculoskeletal diseases are often difficult to obtain’.</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Arthritis Research UK is developing a Musculoskeletal Calculator, an online data tool to provide health planners with local estimates of the numbers of people with musculoskeletal conditions.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The NHS does not routinely record health outcomes measures for most people with musculoskeletal conditions. This is partly because there are no biomarkers (analogous to blood pressure, or blood sugar) for musculoskeletal symptoms like pain and disability. This means that patient reported outcome measures (PROMs) are ideally suited to musculoskeletal health. For example, for those people undergoing hip or knee replacement surgery, the NHS measures and record health before and after their surgery using PROMs. Arthritis Research UK is now working with the musculoskeletal community and NHS England to develop a musculoskeletal patient reported outcome measure (M-PROM) that will have utility for patients, health policy makers and healthcare professionals and can be used across a broad range of musculoskeletal conditions across different clinical settings.</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> This could allow for routine measurement, recording and capture of musculoskeletal health outcomes for most people receiving care for a musculoskeletal health problem.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In April 2013, Public Health England published its priorities for 2013-14.</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> It is regrettable that musculoskeletal conditions were not included in this initial set of priorities. In August 2013 Arthritis Research UK held a stakeholder workshop with Public Health England to explore a public health approach to musculoskeletal health. The workshop considered a </span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">lifecourse</span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> approach to musculoskeletal public health, considering determinants of health, opportunities for health improvement approaches locally and nationally, and considered emerging research questions in the field.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We look forward to Public Health England’s forthcoming framework for health and wellbeing. </span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Musculoskeletal conditions should be systematically incorporated into all Public Health England </span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">workstreams</span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> including in the assessment of population health, the modelling of future public health scenarios and the development of public health interventions.</span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There is a need for Public Health England to focus on outcomes, with proper consideration of how to monitor and measure the success of public health interventions. </span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">As part of Public Health England’s work on the framework for health and wellbeing, there should be a review of the available public health outcome measures that could be used to monitor progress in musculoskeletal health areas. </span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This will ensure that musculoskeletal health is equitably monitored and may identify gaps that should be addressed in future iterations of the Public Health Outcomes Framework. Assessment of national public health should include musculoskeletal conditions and closely integrate with the work undertaken by the CMO.</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Public Health England: roles and responsibilities</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We welcome Public Health England’s responsibility on ‘researching, collecting and analysing data to improve our understanding of health and come up with answers to public health problems’. Given the paucity of musculoskeletal health data, we encourage Public Health England to support the systematic collection of data on musculoskeletal health. </span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Public Health England should work closely with NHS England and the Health and Social Care Information Centre (HSCIC) and others to ensure the routine and systematic collection of data on musculoskeletal health and health-care.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We welcome within Public Health England’s responsibilities inclusion of ‘supporting the public so they can protect and improve their own health’. It is vital that the public has access to accurate and reliable sources of information to help them make informed decisions about their health and wellbeing. Arthritis Research UK has an established role in providing information to inform and empower people with musculoskeletal health problems. </span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Information provision is an area where partnership working between Public Health England and charitable sector would be valuable.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Public Health England has a responsibility for ‘sharing … information and expertise with local authorities … to help them make improvements in the public’s health’. As the largest contributor to years lived with disability, the local impact of musculoskeletal ill health should be included in the Joint Strategic Needs Assessment of every Health and Wellbeing Board. There is currently variable and inconsistent recognition of the burden of musculoskeletal conditions, along with associated risk factors and appropriate public health interventions in Joint Strategic Needs Assessments. Public Health England has an important role to help address this inequality through sharing information and evidence-based solutions, best practice and innovation. Public Health England also has an important leadership role in working with public health professionals in local authorities, highlighting available data and working in partnership with other stakeholders to address data gaps.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As a relatively new body </span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">it is essential that Public Health England continues to build effective working relationships with other national agencies and bodies</span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, in particular:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Other bodies developing public health strategy: for example, NHS England, Department of Health, local authorities and the Office of the Chief Medical Officer for England.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Patient and research charities, as well as the clinical and academic community, who are an important means of understanding and assessing the health and care needs of the population.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Other data-collecting bodies including: HSCIC, Office for National Statistics, and other registries and data sources. For musculoskeletal health such bodies include the National Joint Registry and National Hip Fracture Database.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Research organisations and bodies considering healthcare innovation, such as the NIHR School of Public Health, NIHR/PHE Health Protection Research Units (HPRUs) and the Academic Health Science Network. Public Health England has an opportunity to play a key role in facilitating closer working relationships between public health researchers, practitioners and policymakers.</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="color:#191919; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; vertical-align:baseline">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#191919; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">House of Commons Health Select Committee (2013), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Public Health England accountability hearing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Arthritis Research UK (2010), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Working in partnership towards a future free from arthritis: our research strategy 2010-2015</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Right Care (2011), </span><span style="font-family:Arial